      <p>
        <h1 class="display-4">Technology</h1>
        At the center of all of Polydesk's architecture is the Node.js
        platform &mdash; a proven and powerful JavaScript runtime frequently
        used to drive the server-side or "backend" components of a web
        application. There is a rich ecosystem of third-party libraries offered
        by package registries like <code>npm</code> where code and solutions can
        be shared freely.
      </p>
      <p>
        <h4>ArangoDB</h4>
        ArangoDB is a highly-available multi-model NoSQL database (i.e. it does
        not use SQL for queries) that provides three data model alternatives to
        the classical relational database: document database, graph database,
        and key-value store. You can learn more about these data models and
        ArangoDB <a href="https://www.arangodb.com/why-arangodb/multi-model/" target="_blank">here</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        All document metadata, metadata templates, and structured views are stored
        in document databases in ArangoDB. These are basically lists or
        sets of arbitrary typed data that would normally be stored across
        multiple tables, resulting in complex queries and/or code adapters to
        transform the data from its relational form into a usable structure.
        Using a document database lets us store and retrieve the data with
        a single query. We lose the type constraints enforced by the relational
        models, but make up for this by writing thin adapters on top of the
        ArangoDB query language (AQL) that validate the structure of all data
        that is written to the database.
      </p>
      <p>
        <h4>PostgreSQL</h4>
        PostgreSQL is an open-source relational database with a reputation for
        reliability and performance. The traditional relational database model
        works great for almost any use case, and Polydesk is no exception.
        Everything except document metadata, metadata templates, and structured
        view configurations is stored in PostgreSQL databases.
      </p>
